# Spec Driven Development (SDD)

## Before any feature or refactor

1. Read `AGENTS.md` (project map)
2. Read `docs/memory/STATE.md` (what exists today)
3. Find or create spec in `docs/specs/features/`
4. If no spec exists → use skill `spec-driven-dev` to draft one **before** coding

## Spec hierarchy

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `SPEC.md` | Master product spec (vision, architecture) |
| `docs/specs/features/*.md` | Per-feature specs (requirements, API, UI, acceptance) |
| `docs/memory/STATE.md` | Implementation truth (updated after each feature) |
| `docs/memory/DECISIONS.md` | Architecture decisions (ADR) |
| `docs/memory/PATTERNS.md` | Discovered code patterns |

## Implementation rules

- Code must match active feature spec. Spec conflict → ask user or update spec first.
- Minimal diff: only files listed in spec's "Files affected".
- New API/page/store → update spec **and** `docs/memory/STATE.md` when done.
- Do not implement items marked `Status: planned` in STATE.md unless spec exists.

## After implementation

Run memory update (skill `update-memory`):
- [ ] `STATE.md` reflects new/changed files
- [ ] New patterns → `PATTERNS.md`
- [ ] Non-obvious choices → `DECISIONS.md`
- [ ] Feature spec status → `implemented`

## Spec status values

`draft` → `approved` → `in-progress` → `implemented` → `deprecated`
